# Single-line simple expressions and guards

## Rule

When a statement or JSX tag is simple enough to read on one line, keep it on one line. Do not introduce manual line breaks just because a formatter permits wrapping.

When an `if` exists only to return a value (early exit / guard), put `if`, condition, and `return` on one line. Do not use a braced block for a single `return`.

Immediately after a single-line guard, insert one blank line before whatever comes next. That separates the guard from following logic, including another guard.

Prefer single-line formatting for:

- Short `const` / `let` / `var` initializers, including simple strings and one-call expressions.
- `useRef(false)` / `useState(() => value)` style hook initializers with short comments after the semicolon.
- Short function declarations, component parameter destructuring, and prop types.
- Simple ternaries where both branches are short.
- JSX tags whose props fit comfortably on one line.
- Single-line `if` guards with only `return`.
- Short conditional JSX children, including translation calls and simple ternaries.
- Short mapped expressions and short inline callback updates.
- Simple JSX elements whose only child is a short expression, including translated copy and route data.
- Short function prop types, including single-argument callback types with comments.

## Prefer

```typescript
const ASSISTANT_CHAT_SYSTEM_PROMPT = "You are a helpful assistant for the Ratatouille recipe app. …";
if (!Number.isFinite(userId)) return new Response("Unauthorized", { status: 401 });

const modelMessages = await convertToModelMessages(messages, { tools });
if (!Array.isArray(messages)) return new Response("Expected messages array", { status: 400 });

const commitFromKeyboardReference = useRef(false); /* Avoids firing `onCommit` twice when Enter triggers both keydown and blur */
const [formCommitted, setFormCommitted] = useState(() => isFormMode ? props.defaultValue ?? "" : "");
const hiddenFormValue = isFormMode ? (showInput ? draft : formCommitted) : null;
const pantryOptions = useMemo(() => catalog.map((entry) => ({ value: String(entry.id), label: entry.name })), [catalog]);
const [lines, setLines] = useState<InternalLine[]>(() => withIds(initialLines));
```

