## Avoid

```typescript
const ASSISTANT_CHAT_SYSTEM_PROMPT =
  "You are a helpful assistant for the Ratatouille recipe app. …";

if (!Number.isFinite(userId)) {
  return new Response("Unauthorized", { status: 401 });
}
const modelMessages = await convertToModelMessages(messages, { tools });

const commitFromKeyboardReference =
  useRef(
    false
  ); /* Avoids firing `onCommit` twice when Enter triggers both keydown and blur */

const [formCommitted, setFormCommitted] = useState(() =>
  isFormMode ? (props.defaultValue ?? "") : ""
);

const hiddenFormValue = isFormMode
  ? showInput
    ? draft
    : formCommitted
  : null;

const pantryOptions = useMemo(
  () => catalog.map((entry) => ({ value: String(entry.id), label: entry.name })),
  [catalog]
);

onIngredientsPayloadChange?: (payloadJson: string) => void;
```

```tsx
<h1 className="font-heading text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight">
  {t("auth.signIn")}
</h1>
<p className="text-sm text-muted-foreground">
  {t("auth.magicLinkBlurb")}
</p>

export function RecipeListRowLink({
  recipeId,
  title,
  thumbSrc,
}: RecipeListRowLinkProps) {
  return null;
}

<button
  type="button"
  className={previewZoneGrowSectionClassName}
  onClick={onUploadZoneClick}
>
```

## Exceptions

- Complex expressions, long object literals, long JSX prop lists, and multi-line JSX children can use normal multi-line formatting.
- Do not fight automated formatting for generated files. For hand-edited code, prefer a concise one-line form when it stays readable.
- If a line is genuinely too long to review comfortably, split at a meaningful boundary instead of splitting a trivial expression into many lines.

## Scope

Applies to **new and edited** code in matched files. When editing existing code, avoid churn outside the touched expressions.
